<h3 id="c-language-1">C++ Language:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Single file:</li>
</ul>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">g++ main.cpp <span class="nt">-o</span> binary</code></pre></figure>

<ul>
  <li>Multiple Files:</li>
</ul>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">g++ main.cpp other.cpp <span class="nt">-o</span> binary</code></pre></figure>

<blockquote>
  <p>You can exchange the <code class="highlighter-rouge">g++</code> command for only <code class="highlighter-rouge">c++</code> which is a symbolic link to it:</p>
</blockquote>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="nb">ls</span> <span class="nt">-l</span> <span class="si">$(</span>which c++<span class="si">)</span>
lrwxrwxrwx 1 root 42 Nov 23 19:41/usr/bin/c++ -&gt; /usr/x86_64-pc-linux-gnu/gcc-bin/9.2.0/c++</code></pre></figure>

<h2 id="compiling-with-llvm">Compiling with LLVM:</h2>
<blockquote>
  <p>Clang is a compiler front end for the C, C++, Objective-C, and Objective-C++ languages ​​that uses LLVM as the backend.</p>
</blockquote>

<h3 id="c-language-2">C language:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Single file:</li>
</ul>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">clang main.c <span class="nt">-o</span> binary</code></pre></figure>

<ul>
  <li>Multiple Files:</li>
</ul>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">clang main.c other.c <span class="nt">-o</span> binary</code></pre></figure>

